messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

Full path:
/v1/book

All HTTP methods acceptable:
False

Per-method acceptance (based on the source code):
- HEAD: False
- POST: True
- OPTIONS: False
- TRACE: False
- GET: True
- PUT: False
- DELETE: False
- PATCH: False

Explanation:
- The get_books view is defined with @book_api.route("") inside app/api/v1/book.py. That route is registered on the book blueprint.
- The book blueprint is mounted in app/api/v1/__init__.py with url_prefix="/book".
- The v1 blueprint is registered in app/__init__.py with url_prefix="/v1".
  Combining these gives the full path /v1/book (empty string route on the book blueprint becomes the blueprint prefix path).
- The get_books function does not declare a methods list in its @route decorator, and so the code only defines a GET handler for this path (get_books) — therefore GET is True.
- There is a separate view create_book decorated with @book_api.route("", methods=["POST"]) in the same file, so the same path /v1/book also has an explicit POST handler — therefore POST is True.
- No handler in the source explicitly declares HEAD, OPTIONS, TRACE, PUT, DELETE, or PATCH for the /v1/book path. (PUT/DELETE/PATCH handlers exist only for the /v1/book/<int:id> path, not for /v1/book.) Following the requirement to base acceptance on the code (not on runtime framework behavior), these methods are marked False.
- "All HTTP methods acceptable" is False because the code does not expose a wildcard/all-methods handler.
